As we can see, there are 8 features (plus a name) for every car. Efficiency is quoted in MPG, or miles per gallon. We will now proceed to make a new feature (or column), converting MPG to KMPL (Kilometer Per Liter). 1 MPG = 0.425 KMPL

We shall also add a new feature called hppt which denotes the horsepower generated by the engine per 1000kg of vehicle mass. The calculation is: hp/t = (power * 1000)/weight

d$Mileage <- d$mpg * 0.425
d$hppt <- (d$horsepower * 1000) / d$weight

In the HPPT feature, there is a unique outlier. Let us find it, then remove it for plotting the hppt/acceleration correlation.

d[which.max(d$hppt),]
##                       name mpg cylinders displacement horsepower weight
## 14 buick estate wagon (sw)  14         8          455        225   3086
##    acceleration model_year origin Mileage     hppt
## 14           10         70    usa    5.95 72.90992
d2 <- data.frame(d)
d2 <- subset(d2, hppt < 70)

ggplot(d2, aes(x = hppt, y = acceleration)) + geom_smooth(method = lm, formula = y ~ poly(x, 2)) + geom_point()

cor(d2$hppt, d2$acceleration, use = "complete.obs")
## [1] -0.7461596

Let us now calculate the mean of hp, displacement and mileage for more insights.

mean(d$displacement)
## [1] 193.4259
mean(d$Mileage)
## [1] 9.993693
mean(d$horsepower)
## [1] NA

It seems that the horsepower column has non-integer values in it. Let us recalculate.

mean(d$horsepower, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 104.4694

Results of analysis:

The mean displacement is 193 cubic inches, or about 3.2 Liters. The mean Mileage is about 10 km/L. Mean horsepower is about 105hp.

There is significant sampling bias. These are very old sport cars, ranging from 1970 models to 1982 models. It is clearly noticeable considering the very high mean displacement but with (todays) average horsepower.

Regarding correlations, a negative correlation (-0.78) can be found between Mileage and hp. A strong positive correlation (0.89) is found between horsepower and displacement. The acceleration attribute is the 0-100mph time, therefore a smaller value means faster. This is correlated with hp/t, or the thrust-weight ratio of the car (0.75).

Analyzing key indicators of Heart Disease

by Mugilan

2023-07-04

Let us first load libraries and then the data set.

library(tidyverse)

library(lubridate)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# Loading data
d <- read.csv('./heart_2020.csv')

We shall proceed to find correlations within this data set, to find possible indicators of heart disease.

ggplot(d, 
       aes(x = BMI, 
           fill = HeartDisease)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.4) +
  labs(title = "BMI distribution vs Presence of HD")

As you can notice, patients with HD have a slightly higher BMI than patients without. Here is another plot:

ggplot(d, 
       aes(x = Smoking, 
           fill = HeartDisease)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(y = "Proportion with HD")

It is clearly visible that smoking increases the chance of HD significantly.

ggplot(d, 
       aes(x = AlcoholDrinking, 
           fill = HeartDisease)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(y = "Proportion with HD")

It may be a sampling bias, but according to this data, alcohol consumers have a reduced chance of HD. It also may not be a relevant factor. We shall now investigate the age distribution of HD.

ggplot(d, 
       aes(x = AgeCategory, 
           fill = HeartDisease)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(y = "Proportion with HD")

It is very evident that proportion of people with HD increases with age. Next, we shall explore the connection between Diabetic & HD.

ggplot(d, 
       aes(x = Diabetic, 
           fill = HeartDisease)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(y = "Proportion with HD")

As you can observe, presence of Diabetes massively increases the chance of HD. We will now see if Diabetes and absence of Physical Activity are correlated.

ggplot(d, 
       aes(x = Diabetic, 
           fill = PhysicalActivity)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(y = "Proportion that are Physically Active")

There seems to be a correlation. Diabetic and borderline diabetic patients have a lack of Physical Activity. Next up, General health vs HD.

ggplot(d, 
       aes(x = reorder(GenHealth, desc(HeartDisease)), 
           fill = HeartDisease)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(y = "Proportion with HD", x = "General Health")

There is a very strong correlation between general health and presence of HD. However, it is not easy to determine the direction of the correlation. Finally, we shall explore if HD is correlated with sleep time.

ggplot(d, 
       aes(x = SleepTime, 
           fill = HeartDisease)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(y = "Proportion that have HD")

Sleep durations of 6-8 hours correlate with minimum risk of HD.
